<section id="privacy">
<h2><span class="label">Section 10</span>Privacy Rule (FRBP 9037) Context</h2>
<p>Federal Rule of Bankruptcy Procedure 9037 requires that Social Security Numbers, dates of birth, financial account numbers, and minor-child identifiers be redacted in bankruptcy filings. The Federal Judicial Center&rsquo;s April 2024 empirical study, <em>Unredacted Social Security Numbers in Federal Court PACER Documents</em>, measured compliance across the federal court system.</p>
<div class="callout"><strong>National findings</strong> (Garri et al., 2024): In 37 randomly selected days of 2022 PACER filings, researchers identified <strong>22,391 unredacted Social Security Numbers</strong> affecting approximately 8,300 individuals across 3,521 cases. <strong>72% of identified SSNs appear noncompliant</strong> with the privacy rules. In proof-of-claim filings specifically, the noncompliance rate is <strong>98%</strong>.</div>
<p>A small number of documents account for a disproportionate share of exposure: <strong>45% of unredacted SSNs (10,042) appeared in just 17 documents</strong>, which the authors frame as evidence of systemic actors rather than widespread filer error. The study also documented <strong>54 violations</strong> involving Bankruptcy Form 121 &mdash; the form the court tells debtors &ldquo;will not make publicly available.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The Federal Judicial Center&rsquo;s findings are not broken out by district, and OBP does not publish per-district compliance rates. The FJC study measures <em>appearance of noncompliance</em>, not adjudicated Rule 9037 violations. See the <a href="/research/methodology/#privacy-rule-rule-9037-context">methodology page</a> for why that distinction matters.</p>
<p class="note">Primary source: <a href="https://www.fjc.gov/sites/default/files/materials/30/Unredacted%20Social%20Security%20Numbers%20in%20Federal%20Court%20PACER%20Documents%202024%20Final.pdf" rel="external">Unredacted Social Security Numbers in Federal Court PACER Documents (FJC, April 2024)</a>.</p>
</section>
<section id="recap">
<h2><span class="label">Section 11</span>RECAP Coverage</h2>
<p>Of the 246,551 cases recorded for W.D.N.Y. in the FJC IDB, <strong>0 dockets</strong> (0.0%) are available free of charge in the Free Law Project&rsquo;s <a href="https://www.courtlistener.com/recap/" rel="external">RECAP Archive</a>. Every case link on this site resolves to a free CourtListener page &mdash; no PACER fee, no paywall, no login required.</p>
<p>If the coverage number is lower than you&rsquo;d expect, you can help. Installing the free <a href="https://free.law/recap" rel="external">RECAP browser extension</a> contributes any PACER documents you already pay for to the public archive, at no cost to you.</p>
</section>
<section id="faq" class="faq">
<h2><span class="label">Section 12</span>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<details><summary>How many federal bankruptcy cases have been filed in W.D.N.Y.?</summary><p>According to the Federal Judicial Center Integrated Database, 246,551 cases have been filed in United States Bankruptcy Court for the Western District of New York. W.D.N.Y. ranks 59 of 94 US bankruptcy districts by total filing volume (38th percentile).</p></details><details><summary>What is the chapter mix of bankruptcy filings in W.D.N.Y.?</summary><p>Of classified filings in W.D.N.Y.: Chapter 13 accounts for 50.47% (124,443 cases), Chapter 7 for 48.51% (119,601 cases). The remaining filings consist of Chapter 11 reorganizations, Chapter 12 family farmer cases, and occasional cross-border proceedings.</p></details><details><summary>What happens to bankruptcy cases in W.D.N.Y.?</summary><p>Of 97,759 cases with recorded outcomes (filed FY 2005 onward), 83.29% ended in discharge and 8.24% in dismissal. The remaining cases were converted to a different chapter or closed for other reasons. Cases still open at the last FJC extract are counted separately and excluded from these percentages.</p></details><details><summary>What is the prior-filer rate on Chapter 13 cases in W.D.N.Y.?</summary><p>Of Chapter 13 cases in W.D.N.Y. with prior-filing flags coded, 20.53% had a recorded prior bankruptcy filing. This metric is relevant to 11 U.S.C. § 1328(f) and refiling screening; see the methodology page for detail on how the flag is assigned.</p></details><details><summary>What percentage of bankruptcy cases in W.D.N.Y. are filed pro se?</summary><p>Of W.D.N.Y. filings with representation status coded, 1.74% were filed without an attorney of record.</p></details><details><summary>How many W.D.N.Y. cases are available in the free RECAP Archive?</summary><p>CourtListener&#x27;s RECAP Archive contains 0 dockets for W.D.N.Y., representing 0.0% of FJC IDB-counted cases in this district. RECAP is operated by the Free Law Project; see free.law for attribution and how to contribute.</p></details>
</section>
